Paul Singer, the founder of Elliot is one of the best vultures in the business. In 1996 Elliott bought $11m of debt from Peru and, after legal battles, was repaid $58m, while it also bought bonds worth $10m from the Congo and sued for $400m, ending up with $127m. Elliott’s aggressive stance has been replicated in corporate Europe, where Singer’s son, Gordon runs the UK office.
Another fund that is consolidating much of Lehman’s debt is CarVal – part of an agricultural trading house. The fund has raised $373m since 2008 to buy debt assets that banks divest in the face of new regulations as well as liquidation claims held by banks, brokerages and other creditors.
King Street, is another $20bn New York hedge fund that has turned its attention to the UK arm of Lehman. Its co- founders Brian Higgins and Francis Biondi are renowned distressed debt fund managers and have earned investors around 20pc a year.
The last of the Lehman quar­tet, is Baupost, founded by Seth Klarman, whose book Margin of Safety has awarded him cult status in the annals of American business schools.
Written in 1991 and currently out of print, the book was originally sold for $25. But now used copies exchange hands for up $2,500, with one entrepreneur even renting it out on eBay for $75 a week.
Many of Klarman’s investments seek out distressed securities and bankruptcy work-outs. In the book, he describes buying Texaco bonds in the wake of the company’s sudden 1987 bankruptcy. In the ensuing panic, investors dumped the bonds, and Klarman got them at distressed prices. His bet was that Texaco would make good on the debt, and he was right.
In 2006, Enron’s senior debt was massively mispriced, due to being so impenetrable and legally fraught. Enter Klarman, who bought the debt for 10 to 15 cents on the dollar. Baupost had an analyst work on Enron for four years calculating its liabilities and potential returns. Baupost estimated a recovery of 30 to 40 cents with a margin of safety, believing it might reach 50 cents. It was proved right.
The quartet of consolidators will now be watching PwC very closely to ensure their paper profits are paid out in real cash. In the last biannual report in September, PwC said it had raised £1.8bn in cash from the unit’s assets over the previous six months. After costs, the cash recovered was between £7.5bn and £12.5bn.
Claims from unsecured creditors alone, however, stand at between £16.2bn and £52.5bn. The costs of the administration include the £403m bill PwC has clocked up for working on the case.
Tony Lomas, who heads PwC’s administration of Lehman, said: “The strategy for this year is to make a first distribution to the unsecured creditors and return the planned money – the segregated cash. “There is uncertainty about who is entitled to client money protection.”
