David Cameron should not let Jeremy Heywood investigate 'plebgate', senior Tory says
David Cameron should never let his top civil servant investigate episodes like the Andrew Mitchell "plebgate" scandal because he is too "conflicted", a senior Tory said today.
By Rowena Mason, and Tim Ross
9:30AM GMT 21 Jan 2013
Comments
Bernard Jenkin, chairman of the Public Administration Committee, said an independent adviser should have investigated reports that Mr Mitchell, the Chief Whip, called police officers "f---ing plebs".
The MP said Jeremy Heywood, the Cabinet Secretary, should not be entrusted with inquiries into members of the Government because his main job is to support Mr Cameron.
"The conclusion we reach is that the Cabinet Secretary is likely to have too little time, unlikely to have the necessary skills to conduct such an investigation, and indeed may be conflicted because his primary role is to support the government of the day and support the Prime Minister and keep the wheels on the bus."
A report by Mr Jenkin's committee found Sir Jeremy “failed to uncover the truth” about the altercation between Mr Mitchell and police officers at the gates of Downing Street.
In a report released today, the Public Administration Committee demanded an overhaul of the way allegations against ministers are investigated.
Related Articles
Sir Jeremy Heywood faces Plebgate criticism
21 Jan 2013
Theresa May plans to hire foreign 'supercops'
20 Jan 2013
Fox backs PM on Europe
20 Jan 2013
Robert Key resigns as trustee of former prime minister Sir Edward Heath's charity in funding row
21 Jan 2013
The findings follow Sir Jeremy’s admission that he did not pursue unanswered questions about the scandal.
The Chief Whip resigned after weeks of pressure following his clash with police officers who refused to allow him to cycle through the gates of Downing St. He has admitted swearing but denies calling police “plebs”.
A member of the public who claimed to have witnessed the row was later revealed to have been a police officer. The officer is now the subject of an investigation by the Independent Police Complaints Commission.
Sir Jeremy, who is the government’s most senior civil servant, admitted in evidence to the committee earlier this year that he decided not to pursue the possibility of “a gigantic conspiracy” against Mr Mitchell.
The Prime Minister’s independent adviser on the ministerial code, Sir Alex Allan, should have been asked to investigate instead, the committee said.
However, Sir Alex is not permitted to launch an inquiry unless the Prime Minister asks him to do so.
“We wanted to know what lessons could be learned from the investigation, which clearly failed to uncover the truth,” Mr Jenkin said.
“The Cabinet Secretary attempted to investigate this matter but failed to resolve or even to investigate the questions arising from the discrepancies in the accounts of the events, or to advise the Prime Minister that they required further investigation.
“This underlines the all-too-obvious truth that investigations into ministerial misconduct are not an appropriate role for the Cabinet Secretary to undertake.”
The committee concluded that Sir Jeremy should have recognised the need for a wider inquiry into the unresolved questions and inconsistencies surrounding the incident.
He should have advised the Prime Minister to refer the matter Sir Alex, the MPs said.
