UFC 156: Anthony Pettis offers to fight Jose Aldo as Alistair Overeem pays price for complacency Jose Aldo had barely stamped his authority on the UFC featherweight crown by rebuffing an unremitting Frankie Edgar in his fourth defence of the title in Las Vegas, when UFC President Dana White threw a new challenger into the mix: Anthony Pettis. Image 1 of 2	Hard hitting: Antonio Silva rocks heavyweight rival Alistair Overeem en route to a third round stoppage Image 1 of 2	Bloodied face: Jose Aldo (left) retains the UFC featherweight title for the fourth time against Frankie Edgar By Gareth A Davies
3:24PM GMT 03 Feb 2013
Follow Comments
It was that kind of night – full of surprises – not least when 6ft 5 ins 250lb heavyweight Alistair Overeem was blown out of his title run when Brazilian giant Antonio Silva knocked him down and out under a barrage of third round punches. The modus operandi of these multifaceted fighters is to implement their game plan, but in a sport when styles make – or break -fights, always expect the unexpected. Three out of the five favourites were felled on the main card. But intrigue will grow around a Pettis-Aldo match. Pettis, who arrived in the UFC as a lightweight champion in the buy-out of the WEC fighting organisation, has been forced onto the sidelines with no title shot. The American, who was in action eight days ago and displayed his brilliance in stopping Donald Cerrone, clearly wants the gig. It would be a great matchup. No-brainer in terms of dynamism and mixed martial arts erudition. Why shouldn't Pettis step down a weight while he is forced, at best, to wait six to eight months for a lightweight title shot in the UFC? Whether White – who revealed he had had a text from Pettis ten minutes after the Aldo-Edgar bout offering to fight the champion – will bite is another matter altogether. Related Articles
Aldo v Edgar heralds 'superfight era'
31 Jan 2013
Hatton: boxing can learn from MMA
31 Jan 2013
Hatton: boxers can learn from MMA
31 Jan 2013
Pettis displays brilliance
27 Jan 2013
Johnson retains UFC lightweight title
27 Jan 2013
27 Jan 2013
The Aldo-Edgar 'superfight' card – on pay per view in the United States last night – showcased what we already knew of the two men, but on completion of the five rounds, controversy raged not over the result, but the scoring of the judges as Aldo retained the gold with scores of 49-46, 49-46, and 48-47. The champion was clearly the winner of the opening two rounds, with the third stanza much closer as Edgar began to work resiliently against the heavy kicks and power shots of Aldo, in spite of having all but one of his takedown attempts stuffed. What put the result beyond any doubt was all three judges scoring the third round for Aldo, but the surprise was that Adalaide Byrd and Junichiro Kamijo scored the fifth round to the champion, when he looked to be tiring, but in control, with Edgar still plugging away. Arguably, Edgar may have been landing more towards the end, but the heavier, more damaging shots were being thrown – and landed – by the Brazilian who walked into an MMA gym one day as a homeless street child, but has gone on to become one of the greatest fighters on the planet. Jeff Collins, the third judge Octagonside scored the MMA title fight 48-47, awarding the last two rounds to Edgar. I scored it identically to Collins, 48-47, with Aldo taking rounds 1,2 and the third five-minute round. Aldo began with thudding leg kicks and fast hands in the opening period, his clinical jab reddening the face of the American challenger. By the end of the opening round, the back of Edgar's leading leg had visible welts on it, such was the power of the Aldo 'soccer' kicks landing. Edgar was buckled twice by leg kicks in the second, another round in which the champion outstruck the doughty challenger. The third round was the toughest to score, with Edgar landing a takedown although Aldo got straight to his feet. Edgar then found more success himself with leg kicks, while landing several counters. Yet Aldo's strikes were always the heavier, Edgar ending the round with his face bloodied, and his face showing the wear and tear of the battle, his nose seemingly broken. Undaunted, Edgar – the former UFC lightweight champion – pushed forward relentlessly, seemingly outworking Aldo for the final two rounds, without hurting the champion but outscoring him numerically. Edgar has now lost his last three fights, all title fights. He looked down afterwards, but did not dispute the scoring. **** 'Bigfoot' Silva pulled off the shock of the night at UFC 156 by stopping Alistair Overeem in the third round, a barrage of punches sending the Dutch fighter to the floor as referee Herb Dean intervened for a TKO finish. The brutality of the fight's denouement came suddenly, and emphatically after Overeem had seemed imperious over the opening two rounds. The Dutchman had an air of nonchalance in the opening round, his movement and handspeed clearly far superior. But he dropped his hands and fought with apparent distain for the Brazilian. They looked on different levels for the first ten minutes of the scheduled three rounds. Overeem was clinical and accurate with his attacks, landing a mixture of strikes, and legkicks, targeting both head and body. His body language portrayed an overconfidence which was to later betray him. Having won the opening round, he took the Brazilian down in the second, landing elbows and punches from the top, which were effective more to the huge body of Silva, rather than his downed opponent's head. As the klaxon sounded for the end of the second round, there was very little in the way of offence being offered from the Brazilian. But the adage is never to underestimate an opponent, and respect them at all times. The schoolboy error – or perhaps plain arrogance – cost Overeem in the third round. He appeared to become more ponderous, and he let his guard down as Silva began to apply pressure and get closer. After being caught by a chopping right to the temple, two right hands landed from Silva which took Overeem's senses. Silva pounced and continued his onslaught with three uppercuts, and then crumpled Overeem from a barrage of right and left hands, stamped his big hands like authority across the would-be UFC heavyweight champion's head. Overeem's critics have always argued that he is an 'on top' fighter, and here, he was caught by both the tenacity of Silva, and his own lack of respect for the danger his opponent carries. There are still several mouthwatering matchups for Overeem in the UFC heavyweight division, but this defeat is a reminder of the losses several years ago to Antonio 'Big Nog' Nogueira, Chuck Liddell, and Mauricio Rua. Since then, Overeem may have bulked up, but you cannot graft muscle onto a chin. He clearly paid the price for overconfidence against the Brazilian in this contest. Silva said afterwards: "You fight and win in the Octagon, not by talking bull**** outside. I told him at the press conference that I would make him respect me." “After I knocked him out I was yelling at him ‘Let’s go! I want more … come fight!’ It really bothered me that he hasn’t respected me in interviews leading up to the fight." "He talked a lot of trash and I told him that I’d make him respect me tonight. I’m going to go home and rest with my family for two weeks and then go right back to training. I’m ready for whatever the UFC wants for me next.” Elsewhere on the main card, with all five fights going the full distance, Rashad Evans failed to use his superior handspeed and wrestling in a disappointing spectacle against the younger of the Nogueira brothers. Evans, who some had suggested might have been given a trail leading towards a title shot with UFC middleweight title holder Anderson Silva, a weight division below, was mesmerised into a technical boxing match which suited the Brazilian. Evans failed to use his feints to move inside in order to let his hands go, and paid the price for a sluggish performance. It was arguably the most disappointing display of former 205lbs champion Evans's UFC career. For 'Little Nog', it was the result he wanted, and played out in the manner he would have planned. For that, no one can point the finger at him, in spite of the contest being the least engaging of the entire card in its enactment. Demian Maia dominated Jon Fitch over three rounds spent mainly on the ground. Maia, the BJJ master, stuck to Fitch like a possessive dog with a bone. Fitch's brilliance at wrestling allowed him to defend in difficult positions, but he was unable to shake Maia off to attack with any great meaning himself. It was a shutout 30-27 unanimous decision. The wrestler was outwrestled/outgrappled here, and Maia has enhanced his cause and credentials for a title challenge enormously in the welterweight division. Tyron Woodley made a huge statement on his UFC debut by stopping Jay Hieron in 36 seconds, immediately propelling himself into second tier of the welterweight mix. He may have been stopped by Nate Marquardt in Strikeforce last July, but his wrestling skills and powerful striking could yet take him far in the division. Here he displayed his dangerous, explosive power. Woodley put Hieron down with an overhand right in the opening exchange and then flailed away, his foe clearly unable to come back at him. Woodley will be hailed as a great addition to the UFC welterweight roster, as will another UFC debutant from Strikeforce – Bobby Green – who enjoyed a fine victory over Evan Dunham. Woodley may not be matched with a top contender immediately, but a contest with the loser of Jake Ellenberger/Johny Hendricks or Rory MacDonald and Carlos Condit is certainly not out of the question by the end of this year. Woodley said: “My trainers and I planned to go out there and be explosive. People in the welterweight division need to know that I’m here." "My last few fights have been wars so I was due for a knockout and I’m glad I was able to get it in my UFC debut against a tough guy like Jay. I’m looking forward to fighting a top five guy and continuing to climb the ladder in this division.” Joseph Benavidez handled Ian McCall in a competitive flyweight bout which he won 29-28 by unanimous decision, but he revealed that he is not ready just yet to face UFC flyweight champion Demetrious Johnson again. Benavidez was outfought and outthought in their first title fight encounter. He needs to improve, and look at his strategy, he reckons. As I'd suggested, McCall willingness to come forward and engage, suited Benavidez. Johnson is a different proposition altogether. “I knew he [McCall] was a tough guy. He’s got a bighead that was meant to take a shot," said Benavides a tad unsportingly. "Finishing a guy in the first doesn’t necessarily teach you a lot. You learn way more going the distance with a guy like Ian McCall. My corners didn’t sugar coat it. They told me very clearly that I had to get the third round. It was one to one going into the final five minutes and I had to go out there and take it." "You always want a title shot because that’s what we’re all working for. I had an impressive win over a top guy but I want to continue to grow and be ready when the time comes to take that shot again." UFC 156 full results: Featherweight Jose Aldo (champion) def. Frankie Edgar Decision (unanimous) (49-46, 49-46, 48-47) Rd 5 5:00 Light Heavyweight Antônio Rogério Nogueira def. Rashad Evans Decision (unanimous) (29-28, 29-28, 29-28) Rd 3 5:00 Heavyweight Antonio Silva def. Alistair Overeem KO (punches) Rd 3 0:25 Welterweight Demian Maia def. Jon Fitch Decision (unanimous) (30-27, 30-27, 30-27) 3 5:00 Flyweight Joseph Benavidez def. Ian McCall Decision (unanimous) (29-28, 29-28, 29-28) 3 5:00 Preliminary Card (FX) Lightweight Evan Dunham def. Gleison Tibau Decision (split) (29-28, 28-29, 29-28). 3 5:00 Welterweight Tyron Woodley def. Jay Hieron KO (punches) Rd 1 0:36 Lightweight Bobby Green def. Jacob Volkmann Submission (rear-naked choke) Rd 3 4:25 Lightweight Isaac Vallie-Flagg def. Yves Edwards Decision (split) (29-28, 28-29, 29-28) 3 5:00 Preliminary Card Catchweight (139.5lbs) Dustin Kimura def. Chico Camus Submission (rear-naked choke) Rd 3 1:50 Bantamweight Francisco Rivera def. Edwin Figueroa TKO (punches) Rd 2 4:20
